31 (3) (I) WHEN DETERMINING ELIGIBILITY FOR BENEFITS UNDER
32 THE SUPPLEMENTAL NUTRITION ASSISTANCE PROGRAM, THE DEPARTMENT MAY

14 HOUSE BILL 1331
1 NOT APPLY CATEGORICAL ELIGIBILITY UNDER 7 U.S.C. § 2014(A) OR 7 C.F.R. §
2 273.2(J)(2)(III), UNLESS REQUIRED BY FEDERAL LAW.
3 (II) WHEN DETERMINING ELIGIBILITY FOR BENEFITS UNDER
4 THE SUPPLEMENTAL NUTRITION ASSISTANCE PROGRAM, UNLESS REQUIRED BY
5 FEDERAL LAW, THE DEPARTMENT MAY NOT:
6 1. APPLY A HIGHER GROSS INCOME ELIGIBILITY
7 STANDARD THAN THE GROSS INCOME ELIGIBILITY UNDER 7 U.S.C. § 2014(C); OR
8 2. ALLOW FINANCIAL RESOURCES GREATER THAN
9 THOSE SPECIFIED IN 7 U.S.C. § 2014(G).
10 (4) A HOUSEHOLD ELIGIBLE TO RECEIVE BENEFITS UNDER THE
11 SUPPLEMENTAL NUTRITION ASSISTANCE PROGRAM UNDER FEDERAL AND STATE
12 LAW SHALL REPORT A CHANGE IN CIRCUMSTANCES AFFECTING ELIGIBILITY WITHIN
13 10 DAYS AFTER THE CHANGE OCCURRED, IN ACCORDANCE WITH 7 C.F.R. §
14 273.12(A)(1).
15 (5) IF THE DEPARTMENT RECEIVES INFORMATION CONCERNING AN
16 INDIVIDUAL RECEIVING BENEFITS UNDER THE SUPPLEMENTAL NUTRITION
17 ASSISTANCE PROGRAM THAT INDICATES A CHANGE IN CIRCUMSTANCES THAT MAY
18 AFFECT ELIGIBILITY, THE DEPARTMENT SHALL REVIEW THE INDIVIDUAL’S OR
19 HOUSEHOLD’S ELIGIBILITY.
20 (6) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL ASSIGN REGULAR RECERTIFICATION
21 PERIODS OF NOT GREATER THAN 4 MONTHS, BUT NOT LESS THAN 3 MONTHS, TO
22 HOUSEHOLDS:
23 (I) WITH ZERO NET INCOME;
24 (II) THAT INCLUDE AN ABLE–BODIED ADULT WITHOUT
25 DEPENDENTS; AND
26 (III) WHOSE CIRCUMSTANCES ARE DETERMINED BY THE
27 DEPARTMENT TO BE UNSTABLE.
28 (7) THE DEPARTMENT, IN CONSULTATION WITH LAW ENFORCEMENT
29 AGENCIES, SHALL CONDUCT ANNUAL ON–SITE INSPECTIONS OF RETAIL FACILITIES
30 ACCEPTING ELECTRONIC BENEFITS TRANSFER CARD TRANSACTIONS TO IDENTIFY
31 POTENTIAL FRAUD.

